  "prompt": "If a die is rolled, what is the probability that the number is greater than 4?",
  "response": "When rolling a standard six-sided die, the possible outcomes are the numbers 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6. To find the probability that the number rolled is greater than 4, we need to identify the favorable outcomes and divide by the total number of possible outcomes.\n\nThe numbers greater than 4 are 5 and 6. This means there are 2 favorable outcomes.\n\nThe total number of possible outcomes when rolling a six-sided die is 6.\n\nSo, the probability \\( P \\) that the number rolled is greater than 4 is:\n\n\\[ P(\\text{number} > 4) = \\frac{\\text{number of favorable outcomes}}{\\text{total number of possible outcomes}} = \\frac{2}{6} = \\frac{1}{3} \\]\n\nTherefore, the probability is \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\).",
